## 1  Objective

The objective of this experiment was to study the relationship between
centripetal force, mass, tangential speed, and radius for an object in
uniform circular motion.  The experiment followed the PASCO centripetal
force apparatus idea: a moving mass was constrained to rotate in a
circle, and the inward force required for the circular motion was
measured.

## 2  Theory

For an object of mass \(m\) moving at tangential speed \(v\) in a circle
of radius \(r\), the required centripetal force is

\[
F_c = \frac{m v^2}{r}.
\]

Since \(v = \omega r\), the same relationship can be written as

\[
F_c = m \omega^2 r.
\]

Centripetal force is not an additional force.  It is the net inward
force supplied by the real forces acting on the object.  In this
simulation the real inward force is the spring constraint force, measured
as

\[
F_\text{spring} = k \Delta x.
\]

## 3  Method

The web experiment used a PhysX-native rotating spring model.  A
kinematic rotor was spun at a user-selected angular velocity.  A dynamic
bob rested on a frictionless table and was attached to the rotating frame
by a prismatic joint with a linear drive.  The drive's stiffness and
damping represented the spring tether.  PhysX integrated the bob's
motion; the reported centripetal force was obtained from the measured
spring extension rather than directly from the analytical formula.

