## 6  Data and Error Analysis

The steady-state measured spring force was
{{ "%.5f"|format(summary.mean_force_N) }} N, while the analytical
reference was {{ "%.5f"|format(summary.mean_theory_force_N) }} N.  The
percent difference was {{ "%.3f"|format(summary.force_error_pct) }}%.
The force computed from PhysX-measured speed and radius was
{{ "%.5f"|format(summary.mean_kinematic_force_N) }} N.

The uncertainty estimates used for the simulated sensors were
\(\delta m = {{ "%.5f"|format(summary.mass_unc_kg) }}\) kg,
\(\delta r = {{ "%.4f"|format(summary.radius_unc_m) }}\) m, and
\(\delta v = {{ "%.4f"|format(summary.speed_unc_m_s) }}\) m/s.  Propagating
these through \(F = mv^2/r\) gives an estimated force uncertainty of
{{ "%.5f"|format(summary.propagated_force_unc_N) }} N.

The main deviation occurs during the speed ramp, where the bob is not yet
in uniform circular motion.  During steady state, the spring-force
measurement and the kinematic calculation agree much more closely.

## 7  Conclusion

The result supports the centripetal-force model.  Once the transient
motion decayed, the measured inward spring force agreed with the force
required for circular motion.

1. With radius and speed approximately constant, centripetal force is
   directly proportional to mass.
2. With mass and radius constant, centripetal force is proportional to
   \(v^2\), so a force-versus-speed-squared graph should be linear.
3. With mass and angular velocity constant, \(F_c=m\omega^2r\) predicts
   that force increases with radius.  With tangential speed held constant,
   \(F_c=mv^2/r\) predicts that force decreases with radius.
4. Equation \(F_c=mv^2/r\) is valid.  The radius result depends on
   whether tangential speed or angular velocity is controlled.
5. Friction between the mass and the rotating arm would add an extra
   non-ideal force, reducing speed and contaminating the force sensor
   reading.

